    "summary": "Option B — \"virtue\" in quote, \"constitutive character\" in analysis",
    "content": "B. Use \"virtue\" for the Laozi block quote, then \"constitutive character\" for the author's analysis.\n\nThe epistemological reasoning is straightforward: a quotation and an analysis are different speech acts with different translation obligations.\n\nWhen you quote the Dao De Jing, you're invoking a text that already exists in English. The reader may know it. Using \"virtue\" connects them to the existing translation tradition — Lau, Chan, Legge — and that recognition is epistemically valuable. It tells the reader \"you know this text; now watch what the author does with it.\"\n\nWhen the author then shifts to their own analysis and introduces \"constitutive character,\" the terminological departure itself becomes meaningful. It signals: \"I am not using 德 the way these translators did. I am re-reading this concept.\" The contrast between the quoted \"virtue\" and the analytical \"constitutive character\" enacts the author's interpretive move.\n\nA TN at the transition point can make this explicit: \"The standard English rendering 'virtue' is retained in the block quotation above. In the analysis that follows, 德 is rendered as 'constitutive character' to foreground [the author's specific interpretive claim].\"\n\nThis is cleaner than Option A (which severs the reader from the entire translation tradition for no gain) and more principled than using \"virtue\" throughout (which would flatten the author's departure from conventional readings)."
  }
}
